\title{hatemicoint: Hatemi-J Cointegration Test with Two Unknown Regime Shifts}
\description{
Implements the Hatemi-J (2008) cointegration test which allows for two 
unknown structural breaks (regime shifts) in the cointegrating relationship.
The test provides three test statistics: ADF* (Augmented Dickey-Fuller), 
Zt* (Phillips-Perron Z_t), and Za* (Phillips-Perron Z_alpha), along with 
endogenously determined break dates.
}
\details{
The main function in this package is \code{\link{hatemicoint}}, which 
performs the cointegration test with two structural breaks.

The test is particularly useful when:
\itemize{
  \item Standard cointegration tests fail to reject the null of no cointegration
  \item There is reason to believe the relationship has changed over time
  \item Two structural breaks are suspected in the data
}
}
\section{Test Statistics}{

\describe{
  \item{ADF*}{Augmented Dickey-Fuller test on residuals with optimal lag selection}
  \item{Zt*}{Phillips-Perron Z_t test with kernel-based long-run variance}
  \item{Za*}{Phillips-Perron Z_alpha test with kernel-based long-run variance}
}
}

\section{Critical Values}{

Critical values depend on the number of regressors (k = 1, 2, 3, or 4) and
are taken from Table 1 of Hatemi-J (2008). The null hypothesis of no 
cointegration is rejected when the test statistic is smaller (more negative)
than the critical value.
}

